Software Requirement Specification (SRS):

An SRS is a formal document that serves as the blueprint for the software project. It ensures all developers are aligned and reduces project risk.
Standard SRS Structure
Introduction
Purpose & Scope
Stakeholders
Functional Requirements
Non-Functional Requirements
Assumptions & Constraints
Use Case Diagrams
User Stories & Acceptance Criteria
User Stories
A User Story describes a requirement from the user's perspective.
Template: As a <Role>, I want to <Action>, So that <Benefit>.

Example 1: As a Student, I want to register for an event, so that I can participate in technical competitions.
Example 2: As an Admin, I want to create new events, so that students can register online.
Acceptance Criteria
These define when a feature is considered complete. For a Login Feature, criteria might include:

Valid Email and Password entry.
Successful redirection to the Dashboard.
Error message for invalid credentials.
Secure session creation.
